      <h2 class = missionHead>Our Mission</h2>
      <p class = mission>
        To protect and increase the population of honey bees in the US.
      </p>
      <h2 class = problemHead>The Problem</h2>
      <p class = problem>
        Bee populations have been on the decline for decades. One of the leading causes, beside pesticideas and climate change, is the destruction of their natural habitats. Bees thrive in places like hedgerows and fields of wildflowers, but these environments have been destroyed by infrastructure and urban development. By destroying these environments, not only do bees lose room for foraging and nesting, the quality of the remaining areas can degrade both quickly and exponentially. Also, fragmenting their habitats isolates their species, reducing both the gene flow and genetic diversity in that species. This in turn can increase the bees' vulnerability to parasites and disease. As a result of all these factors, bee population has dropped about 3.6 million hives since 1950, and continues to decline.
      </p>
      <h2 class = factsHead>
       The Un-"Bee"-lievable Truth
      </h2>
      <div class = factsImgDiv>
        <img class = factsImg src =     "https://nitrocdn.com/VRIeDFBZwbZiSpUJcJPgvxtHpuRuggWY/assets/static/source/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/c02f43cd3123f4f9d37dace74e9bbfea.bee-flower-35.jpg" alt = "Honeybee on a flower">
      </div>
      <p class = facts>
        Bees are pollinators, animals that move pollen between plants, which enables those plants to reproduce. 90% of all wild plants and 75% of crops worldwide rely on pollinators. These animals have contributed an estimated 235-577 billion dollars to the US alone in agriculture expenses, and bees are responsible for 80% of all this. Because bees need pollen to feed their young, they are more efficient and hard working than any other pollinator.  
      </p> 
      <h2 class = howHead>Our Plan</h2>
      <div class = howParent>
        <div class = howDiv>
        <p class = how>
          Our goal is to increase the number of beehives located around the US by recording where they already exist, and finding suitable locations for other beehives to be built or relocated. Users can log any beehives they find, whether its in the park or in their backyard. This data is then compiled onto a map, showing the distribution of the bee population. We hope to inspire people to work in their area to bring beehives to places that have too few. Whether it be through sponsoring the construction of a hive through our site, providing a safe environment for a hive to be built, or simply spreading information and awareness, individuals can help increase the honey bee populations in the US.
        </p>
        </div>
        <div class = howImgDiv><img class = howImg src = "https://previews.dropbox.com/p/thumb/AA20I-58qcjkThYvsKjPISpQ-mXcuIPUpQ8dkUyw1wUAZdqh16dYStiS-LO2QYzWNIKRIb-WiFdm03klH81yfLifa9jaVMB1xEp7ne6FDq0N11MU_Ak7vfn2oStklFZE_rLCIEeU_QXnwnhcYb_vpKsHrqCAHONjzXItp2MTT37ocYzAZpDcXoL6Uvcb_yZPReLQ0_jROu9xSkvDXgiLUpOwMeuXn_fvfgyhRPeabtsJyXbEf0DWgsIAktXMG8rugrlUCI5ZFD-VaMlF-6tqQU-qjEi2vM4wFq_3feqDR9ALH2pqAeWzJimE1yNZIQLbuHrZKRdFwySQWMw3jQhTNCPvcrhMUhyNDwNS6Ct3kRDWag/p.png?fv_content=true&size_mode=5" alt = "Beehive Map"></div>
